Inflation in Europe has skyrocketed due to food
The acceleration of inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the constant increase in food prices.
Price growth in November in the 13 countries of the euro area was higher than expected, with annual inflation of 3.1 per cent after 2.6 per cent in October, the Luxembourg statistical office of the Union announced.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, according to Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., U.K. and Canadian issuing banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the base interest rate, with the downturn leading to an inflationary spiral, coupled with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment.
The ECB would like to keep its inflation rate below 2%, but close to it.
According to one of the analysts, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to "defuse" inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation is a record 15 years old at 3.3 per cent, and in Spain it rose from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area has skyrocketed due to sharply rising food and energy prices.
Term wheat prices rose by 88 percent, and soybean prices also reached their highest since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil in world markets rose by 52 percent this year, and last month it already cost one barrel of black gold almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but will drop to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will remain at around 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to double its interest rates in 2008.
