In many places it saves on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection were registered in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff to stop the infection do not help, says the mayor of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, it also saves on disinfectants.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of St. John’s Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been found in a man who arrived at the hospital after a serious traffic accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
The patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after that he had to return with an MRSA infection and due to the bacteria found in his body, one important operation could not be carried out.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1>, Mayor of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, others are not known.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacilin-resistant golden staphylococcus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by a third of people in the nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infection, early infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be well treated.
However, if antibiotics are administered excessively or inappropriately, it will develop from a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics, a bacterium that is highly resistant to antibiotics and that spreads rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with weakened body, low body weight or in patients in years can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief doctor of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections belong to daily practice in hospitals.
"Infection must not be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not just there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the disease-causing agent is not investigated."
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the staff treats them in rubber gloves and masks, and we have antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined if MRSA is present in their body, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions in domestic hospitals are not favorable for preventing the emergence and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs symptomatically in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients admitted and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, the collection of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in fashion.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these examinations also plays a role in this.
Most cases are thus revealed if a patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, said the primary epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic directives for the treatment of individual infections, diseases.
Efforts need to be made to target antibiotic therapy, or microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but even hospitals do not comply in all cases.
The collection of microbiological samples is even rarer in the primary and outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1> said.
It saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most commonly spread among patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, it plays a very important role in washing hands and wearing gloves and masks, but there are also serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and by touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in the conditions of home hospitals.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
As Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1> noted, unfortunately, we can also find that in hospitals, which are in an unfavorable material situation, there are savings on disinfectants, there are few nurses and there are a lot of patients, thus increasing the chances of infection.
According to Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1>, where the necessary protective measures are observed, similar infections are demonstrably less or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is fought against everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA, or reduce its occurrence.
The program appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England show a decreasing trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) places prevention of multi-resistent pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these pathogens among its priorities.
