Banks want to solve the crisis
The U.S. Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
In this way, more than one hundred billion dollars will be brought to the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, banks auction the interest rate at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will send $40 billion to auction, and another twenty-four will be made available to the European and Swiss central banks.
It is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of individual states have agreed on such a coordinated procedure to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This step is intended to address the biggest problems facing the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend,” Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to clients.
"Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to fifty percent," Baumohl said in a statement.
Banks have already lost $60 billion in unpaid loans, particularly in the United States.
Analysts are expecting another billion dollars in losses.
“Central banks need to be really worried about what might come next when they decide to do this,” said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will also lend to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with potential impacts on global economic growth.
The central banks thus decided after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for lending money in the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still concerned about lending money to each other, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"It will have the same effect as the next interest rate drop," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that a move by central banks will help to inflame the crisis because it does not solve the underlying problem, and that is the collapse of the U.S. real estate market.
