Concerns over new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A dispute over gas prices between Russia and Ukraine is currently underway, raising the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is piped through Ukraine and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev warned that if Moscow raises Ukraine’s gas prices, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between the two last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia’s state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more, as it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it receives from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in the course of the negotiations,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinach told Reuters.
“Changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees (to Western Europe) through Ukraine.”
The latest major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused Gazprom to cut supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a crushing drop in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for one-quarter of the supply to the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas supply in the world, but much of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom is replenishing its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
NHS "must check foreign employees"
The inspector said the Scottish chambers of the NHS must improve checks on criminal records of non-European employees.
Recommendations from the president of the Supreme Audit Office, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was linked to the June attacks on Glasgow airport.
Mr Black also fears that the Scottish NHS has no accurate idea of the amount of foreign staff it employs.
But his report emphasized that the other key checks were carried out in an orderly fashion on a sample of five health authorities.
The president of the Supreme Audit Office was interested in staff from countries outside the European Economic Area immediately after the attacks on Glasgow Airport in June.
Eighty-two-year-old Bilal Abdullah, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was detained at the airport after someone hired a Jeep into the door of the main terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Central Criminal Court using a video bridge accused of linking to attempted bombings in the UK.
The NHS is expected to inspect foreign staff for qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK prior to their employment.
Although the Scottish Health Commission uses Disclosure Scotland to check criminal records, this agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report of the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that the commission should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau guidelines, which helps employers with controls in several countries.
"Although we found that part of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out on a regular basis," the report said.
Mr Black said the Scottish NHS is in many ways in line with its own pre-employment screening policy, but also added, “Our report highlights areas where the system could be improved to ensure the availability of accurate information about the number of foreign staff.”
BMA chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS employees who could commit a terrorist act in the future.
"The report suggests that the current pre-employment controls at the Scottish NHS are working well and it is not clear what additional value these comments will bring," he said.
The Scottish health authorities have announced that they currently have 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the president of the Supreme Audit Office pointed out that these numbers will probably be higher also because the commissions had a problem identifying staff with residence permits.
