Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Venus Express, the European space probe on Venus, has recorded phenomena that occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and wind gusts at the poles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is glowing.
Now the European probe Venus Express has brought proof - it has captured electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, lightning flies from cloud to cloud at a height of about 56 kilometers, wrote in the scientific magazine Nature Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles.
According to a well-known theory of the origin of the primordial matter, life could have been created on Earth by lightning. Storms allegedly triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the basic stones of life.
“If there ever was life there, it must have been a long time ago,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and sometimes there are temperatures of around 500 °C on the surface of Venus.
"He may be the hellish twin of the Earth, but he's the twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to the Earth in mass and size, began to evolve in a completely different way, is a fundamental question of the mission of Esa.
Since no spacecraft has been sent for the study of Venus since the early 1990s, the launch of Venus Express in November 2005 has been a milestone in the exploration of this planet.
According to scientists, the latest results of the research, which brought together several articles in the journal Nature, did not only emphasize the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
"They also showed that our neighboring planet is more Earth-like than previously thought," said Esa.
In addition to the already known winds at the North Pole, scientists have found a dark swirl at the South Pole that spins much faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth's northern hemisphere, writes a research team led by Guiseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrophysics Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of our solar system is almost the same mass as the Earth and with an average of 12,100 km it is almost the same size.
This planet, known as the Morning Star or Evening Star, will orbit the Sun in about 225 days.
However, it rotates much slower around its own axis, with one day on Venus lasting 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus is not reminiscent of a surface temperature of 460°C and a pressure of 92 bar Earth, scientists believe that the two planets originated under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, but on Earth it remained in the oceans, while it evaporated from Venus into space.
While carbon dioxide on Earth is bound in carbonates, it forms most of the atmosphere on Venus.
