These aren't Warhol's boxes.
If you combine the terms Sweden and wooden boxes, you don't think of Andy Warhol, you think of Ikea.
Or is it?
Wooden boxes currently manufactured in Sweden cast dark shadows on the list of Warhol's works.
Most of his list of ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago expressed doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's "Brillo Boxes" in 1968, the internal research of the Moderna Museet Museum in Stockholm comes with a result that brought disappointment; six "Brillo Boxes" are more than his "Brillo Boxes", which in 1995 were donated to the Moderna Museet.
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curative events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painted wooden boxes that were based on the reddish-brown design of paper boxes of Brillo soap powder.
The exhibition of his works in the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their designs, just exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to produce several wooden Brillo beds in Sweden, but these are not on display in the Moderna Museet.
The witnesses of the time now speak of fifteen boxes that at that time rightly entered the artistic and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred bends were made and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hulten bends were produced in Malmö for the exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the top conservator of the Moderna Museet, explored in addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, also three Brillo boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood plates were painted with a varnish on the base.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, revealed that the paint was applied directly to the plywood board by the painter's role without the previous base paint - in addition, it is acrylic, not oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo box list," said Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board's classification of materials in New York does not come to any other conclusions, Moderna will be
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would address these “core charges” in the case of soap powder boxes.
But the organization is still in inexorable silence.
Rebel soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers fortified themselves in a hotel in Manila and demanded the resignation of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Insurgent commander Antonio Trillanes, who denounced the president's manipulation and corruption in the election, told reporters at the hotel that he denied responsibility for the bloodshed.
Soldiers loyal to the government had previously attacked the hotel with tear gas.
A few hours before, about two dozen soldiers had fortified in the building.
On Thursday, about half of them were on trial for a failed coup attempt in 2003, including Trillanes.
He took advantage of the negotiations to flee with about 30 of his sympathizers.
The military policemen who were supposed to guard him apparently rushed to his side and joined the rebellion.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the resignation of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government loyalists have closed the area around the selected hotel.
The president called for an urgent meeting of the security cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have had enough," Triallnes said.
"We are calling on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, commander of the former elite Scout Rangers, said more troops would join the march in a short time.
Critics of the government called for a major demonstration against the president on Friday.
For months her government has been plagued by corruption.
In 2003, the Manila financial district became the main site of a rebellion of about 200 soldiers against Arroyo.
Because the rebels refused to join the army, the rebellion collapsed after less than 24 hours.
Since 1986, at least seven attempts have been made to overthrow a democratically elected government in the Philippines.
